The whole of Bolivia's inland state has still recovered the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 1800s, and the country is longing for once again to sail in the Pacific.
These hopes may be greater than they have been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court on 1 October after five years of discussion.
‘Bolivia has a driving force, a Community spirit and calmness of mind and, of course, awaits the outcome with a positive attitude’, said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court of Justice on a large scale in many different places in the country, hoping that the Hague court will give its opinion in favour of Bolivia’s claim that Chile — after several decades of sporadic negotiations — is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia its own way to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president — facing a controversial re-election campaign next year — has also invested a lot in Monday’s feeling.
«We are very close to a return to the Pacific,» he promised late in August.
But some analysts believe that the court will hardly take Bolivia's party, and that very little would change if it had.
The UN agency, which is the team of the Netherlands, has no authority to allow them to give up Chilean land, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
According to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law, that the judgment of the International Court comes only six months after the last arguments were heard.
And rather than promoting Bolivia's case, the last four years may have actually made things worse.
‘The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration’, said Zárate.
She believes that Morales' antagonistic rhetoric has wiped out any remaining goodwill on the part of Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations on one point or another, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter afterwards.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative at The Hague, rejected the theory that the decision of the Court of Justice came unusually quickly.
According to him, Monday will give Bolivia ‘an exceptional opportunity to open up a new generation of relations with Chile’ and the opportunity to ‘stop 139 years of disagreement, for the benefit of both parties’.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales — still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America — had used the maritime situation as a political cover.
