A new course at Harvard University this year will help students to get more sleep by tackling the growing unculture of pooping through the night with coffee drinks as fuel.
An academic found out that students at the world's best university often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after he gave a lecture on the effect sleep deprivation has on learning.
"After the talk, a girl came to me and said, "Why hasn't anyone said this before?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and it surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to the students the importance of good sleep habits in order to be able to perform academically and sportingly, and in the general state.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and adm. dir. for university health services, said that the university decided to start the course after they saw that the students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of a room in a dorm, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, jogging shoes and books and hear about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
In another part, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
«We are aware that this will not change the behaviour of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know about this, just as you have the right to know about the risk of smoking," said Professor Czeisler.
There's still some pride in being able to pry all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on the students led to an increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Enough and good sleep should be the students' ‘secret weapons’ against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even as a remedy for weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of hunger, leading to constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course.
He said that the course inspired him to work for a course that was available for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all the master's students to take a similar study programme before they are enrolled in the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that the students set an alarm for when to lie down as well as for when to get up, and that they should be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LED lights.
