What is unique about the online personal data repository is that it is up to the user who should have access to that type of information.
The company calls it ‘personal authorisation through data’.
According to the company's CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company should provide resources, process and relevant competence to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some hired developers on contract to work with the project and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about introducing something completely new or not, which will make their business models completely recalibrated overnight.
«We are not asking for their permission».
In an article on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's " mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994 Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on online neutrality.
Although he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will still be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
