The fateful F125 frigate made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss yard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the marine has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the causes of the return, but German media mentioned a number of important ‘software and hardware defects’ that made the warship useless in a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important since ships in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class will be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors - only half of the crew of older frigates in the Bremen class.
It was also discovered that the ship has a huge preponderance, which reduces performance and limits the marine's ability to make upgrades in the future.
