The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as browning and water-flagging mice at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special photocopiers will be deployed at important locations around the property to track seasonal bat activity.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and the species that do.
A habitat map and a report will then be prepared to provide a detailed landscape of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the installation of pastures and the best management of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction that affects breeding grounds and habitat degradation.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attack from house taxes.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than for their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road when they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten competent experts who regularly carry out surveys, survey breeding grounds and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Three Landings in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threeve we have a perfect area for bats," he says.
«We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He underlines the importance of mapping the bats before carrying out maintenance on a property since accidental destruction of a single breeding site may kill up to 400 females and young people, and may obliterate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or disturb them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the audience to help in the work.
She says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we just don't know how the populations are doing."
