The United States has now lost six times in succession on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the throne when the Danish team captain Thomas Bjørn got the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
The U.S. star Phil Mickelson, who played during large parts of the tournament, avoided his tea-beats in the water at par-3, 16th holes, and had to see himself turned off by Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was brilliant at all his rounds and became 1 out of 4 golfers who have ever gone 5-0-0 since the tournament got its current design in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was knocked out 5 and 4 of the lowest ranked player on the European team, Thorbjørn Olesen from Denmark.
The world's most ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to Ian Poulter from England, who may have played his last Ryder Cup final.
With all eight Ryder Cup tournaments behind them, Spanish Sergio Garcia became the most winning Europeans of the tournament over the ages with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t stop.
It's been a tough year.
I'm so grateful that Thomas picked me out and had faith in me.
I'm very, very happy to get back the cup.
It's about the team, and I'm glad I could be of help," said an emotional Garcia after the European winner.
He leaves the baton to his compatriot John Ram, who beat the American golf legend Tiger Woods 2 and 1 in single games on Sunday.
"I'm incredibly proud to beat Tiger Woods – I followed that man closely in his youth," said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four matches in France and now has a record of 13-21-3 career points in the Ryder Cup.
A strange statistic for one of the biggest golfers ever, who has won 14 major titles, just turned off Jack Nicklaus.
Team United States spent the whole weekend finding the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played high-precision golf throughout the tournament.
United States team captain Jim Furyk spoke up after a disappointing achievement for his troops, "I'm proud of these guys, they fought.
It was moments this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We threw ourselves.
The hat off for Thomas.
He's a great team captain.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We want to regroup, I want to work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Committee and I want to look ahead.
I love these 12 guys, and I'm proud to be their team captain.
You just have to take off your hat.
We were beaten."
Algal bloom update: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Fisheries and Animal Life Commission (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, spotty blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County — suggesting reduced concentrations.
A flowering of red algae stretches about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are discovered about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Reddalger has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County have been reported in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No respiratory irritation was reported northwest of Florida in the last week.
